This is a follow-up to #35667.

See https://github.com/dotnet/roslyn/pull/35667#issuecomment-507758934.

### Sample code

```csharp
/// <summary>
/// <code>
/// code line 1
/// code line 2
/// </code>
/// </summary>
private int value;
```

### Expected result

Quick Info for `value` renders the summary code as a two-line code block with code font.

### Actual result

Quick Info for `value` renders the summary code on one line with code font.

**Example**
```
class C
{
	private string _a;
	private string _bb;
	private string _cccc;

	void M()
	{
		_a    = "a";
		_bb   = "b";
		_cccc = "c";
	}
}
```

**Problem**
`csharp_space_around_binary_operators` also affects assignments.
This is not always desirable. The example above should not be reformatted.
There is currently no way to enforce `csharp_space_around_binary_operators` and
ignore spaces in assignments.

**Proposal**
Handle the assignment operator (=) with a new rule:
`csharp_space_around_assignments = [before_and_after|ignore]`

